1 help consumers achieve their independent living goals.
2 (6) "Severe visual impairment" means a visual disability that, even with correction, remains so
3 severe that it makes daily tasks difficult to perform.
4
5 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Eligibility for services. The department shall determine whether a
6 person is eligible for independent living services based on criteria established by the department through
7 administrative rule as provided in [section 6].
8
9 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Services provided -- evaluation of consumer needs. (1) The
10 department may provide the following independent living services:
11 (a) outreach;
12 (b) services, training, and assistive technology to help consumers become more mobile and self-
13 sufficient;
14 (c) Braille instruction and other services and equipment to help consumers adjust to a severe
15 visual impairment;
16 (d) independent living skills training;
17 (e) peer counseling;
18 (f) guide services and reader services; and
19 (g) any other appropriate service designed to help consumers achieve their independent living
20 goals.
21 (2) The department shall evaluate each consumer to determine the independent living services
22 that may help the consumer achieve the consumer's independent living goals.
23 (3) To the extent that the department determines the program has funds available, the department
24 may provide or pay the cost of independent living services for a consumer. When determining the services to
25 be provided, the department shall consider the financial resources available to the consumer and the needs of
26 other consumers.
27
28 NEW SECTION. Section 5. Fair hearing. A person with a severe visual impairment who applies for
